of these delays.

84
00:07:09,186 --> 00:07:12,627
At least consumers largely seem to understand

85
00:07:12,627 --> 00:07:15,108
the struggles that everybody is going through

86
00:07:15,108 --> 00:07:16,728
in terms of COVID right now.

87
00:07:18,410 --> 00:07:19,751
But this was demoralizing.

88
00:07:19,751 --> 00:07:26,773
We managed to hit out of production around late May and

89
00:07:26,773 --> 00:07:27,693
hit it into post-production.

90
00:07:27,693 --> 00:07:30,994
And then in August, 27th, we managed to release, and I still

91
00:07:30,994 --> 00:07:37,197
can't quite believe this happened because it just, it's.

92
00:07:37,498 --> 00:07:41,865
so hard to release the game during during this late in the middle of this

93
00:07:41,865 --> 00:07:46,754
climate. I am so proud of my team and like sometimes I still think about how

94
00:07:46,754 --> 00:07:48,857
amazing and

95
00:07:49,295 --> 00:07:55,937
impressive it was to be able to get this game out with all these challenges going on in the background.

96
00:07:55,937 --> 00:08:03,240
It shows immense mental and emotional fortitude to achieve something like this.

97
00:08:03,240 --> 00:08:09,562
And then we moved into live ops afterwards, which was quite an intense period, the immediate

98
00:08:09,562 --> 00:08:12,143
post-launch maintenance period.

99
00:08:12,763 --> 00:08:18,504
And I feel like this is really when the emotional cost of development was at its highest.

100
00:08:18,504 --> 00:08:21,645
It was a really intense and difficult time.

101
00:08:21,645 --> 00:08:25,466
And around November, the intense live ops kind of ended,

102
00:08:25,466 --> 00:08:31,887
and then it just went onwards indefinitely in terms of supporting the game.

103
00:08:31,887 --> 00:08:38,248
Like, technically, the game is still not complete because we are always updating it,

104
00:08:38,248 --> 00:08:41,188
we're always adding patches, we're always adding extra content.

105
00:08:41,188 --> 00:08:41,328
So...

106
00:08:42,549 --> 00:08:44,390
It's not really, is it ever really done?

107
00:08:44,390 --> 00:08:47,112
I guess is the question.

108
00:08:47,112 --> 00:08:50,574
So heading into release window in August,

109
00:08:50,574 --> 00:08:52,175
we were already tired.

110
00:08:52,175 --> 00:08:55,597
We were at the usual end of Project Fatigue

111
00:08:55,597 --> 00:08:56,858
where the last 10% takes 90% of the work.

112
00:08:56,858 --> 00:08:59,700
And this was also our first title.

113
00:08:59,700 --> 00:09:03,082
So we poured a lot in trying to make the game,

114
00:09:03,082 --> 00:09:07,525
make our mark as a lot of indies do with their first title.

115
00:09:08,594 --> 00:09:13,981
We were demoralized from announcing delays and pushing back our release three times.

116
00:09:13,981 --> 00:09:18,067
It was an understandable disappointment for my community.

117
00:09:18,067 --> 00:09:23,415
It was a disappointment to us because we just really wanted to share what we have been working

118
00:09:23,415 --> 00:09:24,577
on.

119
00:09:25,645 --> 00:09:30,848
And outwardly, it seems like delays can mean a reprieve in terms of work,

120
00:09:30,848 --> 00:09:35,051
but as developers, you understand that a delay just means a longer time

121
00:09:35,051 --> 00:09:37,453
until the payoff of release.

122
00:09:37,453 --> 00:09:41,035
It means a long time working on the same project and a longer time

123
00:09:41,035 --> 00:09:45,338
before you see the revenue generation from the game, which is,

124
00:09:45,338 --> 00:09:49,000
you know, a studio owner is an extra stressor.

125
00:09:49,000 --> 00:09:54,344
We were already demoralized from these delays, and we

126
00:09:55,980 --> 00:10:01,565
really wanted to share what we thought was like a utopian story that the world needed at that point.

127
00:10:01,565 --> 00:10:02,266
We were already stressed

128
00:10:02,266 --> 00:10:09,071
mostly because there were so many unknown surrounding release and this was true before COVID.

129
00:10:09,071 --> 00:10:15,577
But especially during the pandemic these stresses were exacerbated in terms of

130
00:10:15,577 --> 00:10:22,422
you know, whether it would be received well, what the reviews would say, what issues might be cropping up that need triaging and patching.

131
00:10:23,083 --> 00:10:28,506
But also because we had encountered so many roadblocks coming up to this point,

132
00:10:28,506 --> 00:10:32,109
it almost felt like when is the other shoe going to drop?

133
00:10:32,109 --> 00:10:37,592
Not knowing how external partners were going to manage their own processes

134
00:10:37,592 --> 00:10:42,135
amidst their own COVID situations, which is super difficult to navigate.

135
00:10:42,135 --> 00:10:45,398
Not being able to estimate timelines

136
00:10:45,398 --> 00:10:49,960
when dates are like the holy grail in the games press cycle.

137
00:10:50,943 --> 00:10:58,766
not being able to perform at the same level of quality and finesse as releases pre-COVID,

138
00:10:58,766 --> 00:11:05,969
you're expected to still meet that bar, despite the fact that the world stage is completely different right now.

139
00:11:05,969 --> 00:11:10,791
But we were excited because we'd been working on this for a year and a half.

140
00:11:10,791 --> 00:11:13,332
We were passionate about it. We loved the project.

141
00:11:13,797 --> 00:11:18,418
and we had seen people love playing it at shows, we had a community that had started to build around

142
00:11:18,418 --> 00:11:23,600
that that was very supportive and very kind, and we just wanted to contribute this positive

143
00:11:23,600 --> 00:11:28,962
story to a world that was currently turned upside down. And we were glad it was out, but it wasn't

144
00:11:28,962 --> 00:11:37,586
done. We pushed the button and it released, but it's never done once you do that. I'm definitely

145
00:11:37,586 --> 00:11:43,148
not saying anything in this talk just to be clear that this is gospel or anything, but

146
00:11:44,422 --> 00:11:52,571
Personally, my experience of this immediate post-launch time period was the most difficult

147
00:11:52,571 --> 00:12:02,382
part of the whole production cycle. Even bug squashing and other roadblocks that we encountered

148
00:12:02,382 --> 00:12:04,404
wasn't as draining as this was.

149
00:12:04,971 --> 00:12:10,056
launches your one chance at the moment to legitimize the purpose of your entire production cycle,

150
00:12:10,056 --> 00:12:16,542
a year and a half of work, the investment of a significant period of time to create one thing,

151
00:12:16,542 --> 00:12:21,988
to prove your concept fully in terms of realization and reception,

152
00:12:21,988 --> 00:12:25,311
and likely your biggest chance to make your mark with this artifact.

153
00:12:25,893 --> 00:12:32,879
And as in recent past we can see the zeitgeist coming back around and sometimes that does happen.

154
00:12:32,879 --> 00:12:38,825
It's super rare and the botched launch is something that never fails to make headlines in games.

155
00:12:38,825 --> 00:12:45,571
It's all in all at once and launch has an immense amount of pressure tied to it because of this.

156
00:12:47,783 --> 00:12:52,866
So, Pain Point 1, I feel the emotional cost of launching games

157
00:12:52,866 --> 00:12:54,787
encompasses several pain points.

158
00:12:54,787 --> 00:12:57,970
The first of which being the end point of production

159
00:12:57,970 --> 00:12:59,851
is becoming extremely ephemeral.

160
00:12:59,851 --> 00:13:03,013
Some of the emotional drain from these launch windows

161
00:13:03,013 --> 00:13:06,435
definitely seems to stem from the amount of unpredictability

162
00:13:06,435 --> 00:13:08,757
that comes with pressing the release button.

163
00:13:09,016 --> 00:13:15,400
The immediate period after launch can be busy keeping up with press, communicating with the community.

164
00:13:15,400 --> 00:13:23,324
These are all incredibly time-consuming and sometimes exhausting activities that come at the end of an already full development cycle.

165
00:13:23,324 --> 00:13:25,686
But even aside from that, it seems like...

166
00:13:26,565 --> 00:13:30,326
we're almost going towards games a continual service,

167
00:13:30,326 --> 00:13:33,747
not the sense that games are a service and free to play.

168
00:13:33,747 --> 00:13:36,689
